---
import Layout from "@/layouts/main.astro";

const title = "Mouse Accuracy & Fine Motor Control Science | CogniArena";
const description = "Explore motor unit recruitment patterns, Fitts's Law index of difficulty, and sub-pixel coordinate targeting for precision pointing.";
const canonicalUrl = "https://cogniarena.com/learn/mouse-accuracy";

const schemaJson = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "Article",
  "headline": "Science of Mouse Accuracy and Fine Motor Precision",
  "description": "Examine motor unit hierarchy, Fitts's Law difficulty indexing, and sub-pixel coordinate control in computer pointing tasks.",
  "author": {
    "@type": "Person",
    "name": "Dr. Alan Vanc",
    "jobTitle": "Neuroscience Researcher"
  },
  "publisher": {
    "@type": "Organization",
    "name": "CogniArena"
  }
};
---

<Layout title={title} description={description} canonicalUrl={canonicalUrl} schemaJson={schemaJson}>
  <div class="flex flex-col gap-12 w-full max-w-3xl mx-auto">
    <header class="flex flex-col gap-3">
      <div class="flex items-center gap-2 text-xs font-mono uppercase tracking-widest text-accent">
        <span>Learning Center</span>
        <span>&middot;</span>
        <span>Pillar Page</span>
      </div>
      <h1 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground animate-fade-in">
        Mouse Accuracy & Fine Motor Control Science
      </h1>
      <p class="text-muted text-sm md:text-base leading-relaxed">
        A scientific examination of motor unit recruitment, Fitts's Law difficulty indices, and the biomechanics of precision cursor control.
      </p>
    </header>

    <section class="flex flex-col gap-10 border-t border-card-border pt-10">
      <article class="flex flex-col gap-4">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-foreground tracking-tight">1. Motor Unit Recruitment and Graded Control</h2>
        <p class="text-muted text-sm leading-relaxed">
          Fine motor control of the hand and fingers relies on small motor units innervating as few as 10 to 100 muscle fibers per neuron. The smallest motor units, located in the intrinsic hand muscles, are recruited first according to Henneman's size principle, allowing graded force output from 0.1g to 500g. The ratio of motor unit recruitment threshold to maximum force determines the precision ceiling: smaller units allow finer gradation, which is why finger movements achieve higher accuracy than wrist or arm movements.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article class="flex flex-col gap-4">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-foreground tracking-tight">2. Fitts's Law Index of Difficulty</h2>
        <p class="text-muted text-sm leading-relaxed">
          The index of difficulty in Fitts's Law is computed as ID = log₂(D/W + 1), where D is movement distance and W is target width. Doubling the distance increases ID by approximately 1 bit, while halving the target width also increases ID by 1 bit. For mouse accuracy tasks, small targets with ID values above 5 bits begin to exceed the comfortable control range for most users, requiring corrective submovements and revealing the stochastic nature of neuromuscular noise. The Shannon formulation has been shown to account for more variance in pointing performance than the original Welford formulation.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article class="flex flex-col gap-4">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-foreground tracking-tight">3. Sub-Pixel Coordinate Targeting</h2>
        <p class="text-muted text-sm leading-relaxed">
          Modern mice report cursor coordinates at resolutions of 800 to 3200 CPI, yet the operating system ultimately snaps to integer pixel coordinates. Sub-pixel targeting involves the brain and motor cortex predicting cursor trajectories with fractional precision, then executing corrective micro-adjustments to land within a one-pixel target window. The visual system can detect positional offsets as small as 0.1 arcminutes, but transforming this sensory information into sub-pixel motor commands requires extensive calibration between visual error signals and motor output gain.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article class="flex flex-col gap-4">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-foreground tracking-tight">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
        <div class="flex flex-col gap-4 text-sm">
          <div>
            <h4 class="text-foreground font-bold mb-1">What factors affect mouse accuracy the most?</h4>
            <p class="text-muted">Mouse CPI setting, monitor resolution, target size, and movement distance all interact through Fitts's Law. Neuromuscular noise and hand tremor add stochastic variance that sets a floor on achievable accuracy.</p>
          </div>
          <div>
            <h4 class="text-foreground font-bold mb-1">How can I improve my clicking precision?</h4>
            <p class="text-muted">Use a consistent CPI setting, optimize target size-to-distance ratios, and practice aiming tasks that require absolute accuracy. Training reduces endpoint variability through motor cortex refinement.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </article>
    </section>

    <p class="text-muted text-sm leading-relaxed text-center border-t border-card-border pt-10">
      Measure your aiming precision on the <a href="/tests/mouse-accuracy" class="text-accent underline underline-offset-2 hover:brightness-110 transition-all">Mouse Accuracy Test</a>.
    </p>
  </div>
</Layout>
